    "body": "I have a workaround that is to change `AliasManger.init_aliases` in `IPython/core/alias.py` to\r\n\r\n    def init_aliases(self):\r\n        # Load default & user aliases\r\n        for name, cmd in self.default_aliases + self.user_aliases:\r\n            if cmd.startswith('ls ') and self.shell.colors == 'NoColor':\r\n                cmd = cmd.replace(' --color', '')\r\n            self.soft_define_alias(name, cmd)\r\n\r\nDo you think this an acceptable solution? If yes I can submit the pull request.\r\n\r\nI don't quite understand what is a `Configurable` and what does `List(default_aliases()).tag(config=True)` imply. Why should the `default_aliases` be a class data member instead of instance data member? If it is an instance data member, we can easily let the function `default_aliases()` take a parameter `nocolor` and when it is `False` do not set `--color` in the aliases for `ls`."
  },
